  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best way to find out how many people search for specific keywords online?",
  "response": "To find out how many people search for specific keywords online, you can use various tools that provide search volume data and keyword analytics. Here are some of the most effective methods:\n\n1. **Google Keyword Planner**: This tool is part of Google Ads and is designed to help advertisers choose keywords for their campaigns. It provides valuable data on search volumes and trends for specific keywords. You will need a Google Ads account, but using the Keyword Planner does not require you to run an actual ad campaign.\n\n2. **Google Trends**: This tool offers insights into the popularity and search trends of specific keywords over time. While it doesn\u2019t provide exact search volume figures, it shows relative popularity and helps identify emerging trends.\n\n3. **SEMrush**: A comprehensive SEO tool that provides detailed keyword analytics, including search volume, keyword difficulty, and competitive data. SEMrush is a paid tool, but it offers a wealth of information for digital marketing professionals.\n\n4. **Ahrefs**: Known for its extensive backlink analysis, Ahrefs also offers robust keyword analysis features. It provides search volume data, keyword difficulty, and insights into the websites currently ranking for specific keywords.\n\n5. **Ubersuggest**: Created by Neil Patel, Ubersuggest offers keyword suggestions, search volume data, and competition analysis. It also provides insights into content ideas and trends.\n\n6. **Moz Keyword Explorer**: This tool provides keyword recommendations and analysis, including search volume and difficulty scores. Moz also offers a free trial for users to test its features.\n\n7. **AnswerThePublic**: While primarily focused on providing content ideas based on common search queries, AnswerThePublic can complement other tools by highlighting the questions and phrases people frequently search for related to specific keywords.\n\n8. **Keywords Everywhere**: This browser extension provides search volume, cost-per-click (CPC), and competition data for keywords directly in your search engine results page. It\u2019s a convenient option for quick insights without switching tools.\n\n9. **Bing Keyword Research Tool**: Similar to Google Keyword Planner but for the Bing search engine, this tool can be useful if you\u2019re interested in Bing\u2019s search environment.\n\nEach tool has its own strengths, so consider what additional features or data you might need when choosing one. Some tools offer free versions or trials, which can be helpful for exploring your options before committing to a subscription.",
